3 September 1296":"1255–3 September 1296","1255–1296":"1255–1296","1262–1289":"1262–1289","1254–1296":"1254–1296","1273–1333":"1273–1333","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1242–1275":"1242–1275","Aft 1275":"after 1275","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1262":"1262","1272":"1272","28 April 1296":"28 April 1296","1270":"1270","3 September 1296":"3 September 1296","1245":"1245","1333":"1333","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","Stitchill, Roxburghshire, Schotland":"Stitchill, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Huntly, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Huntly, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"McDuff","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Duibh</b>, a patronymic from the personal name or byname <i>Dubh</i> ‘black, dark-haired, swarthy’. Compare   Duff  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Duff","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’, used both as a nickname and a personal name. In Scotland, it is typically a descriptive epithet for a dark-haired man (compare   Dow   1). In Ireland, it is usually from <b>Ó Duibh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubh</i>’ or <b>Mac Giolla Duibh</b> ‘son of the servant of <i>Dubh</i>’. It is also found as a short form of   Duffin   and a variant of   Duffy  . See also   McDuff  .","In some cases possibly also a shortened form of Breton   Le Duff  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"McDow","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McDuff  ."]},{"name":"McGuff","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Dhuibh</b>, a patronymic from the personal name or byname <i>Dubh</i> ‘black, dark-haired, swarthy’. Compare   McDuff  ."]}]},{"name":"Marjorie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual modern spelling of   Margery .  It seems to have arisen as the result of folk etymological association of the name with that of the herb <i>marjoram</i> (  compare  Rosemary  ). This word is of uncertain origin; its Middle English and Old French form was <i>majorane</i>, without the first <i>-r-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marjory","meanings":["The usual modern spelling of   Margery .  It seems to have arisen as the result of folk etymological association of the name with that of the herb <i>marjoram</i> (  compare  Rosemary  ). This word is of uncertain origin; its Middle English and Old French form was <i>majorane</i>, without the first <i>-r-</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marjorie McDuff was born in 1255, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Mormaer Colban MacDuff 8th Earl of Fife, was 10 and her mother, Lady Anne Durward, was 14. She married Adam de Gordon 6th Laird of Gordon in 1272, in Stitchill, Roxburghshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 3 September 1296, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1255–3 September 1296":"1255–3. september 1296","1255–1296":"1255–1296","1262–1289":"1262–1289","1254–1296":"1254–1296","1273–1333":"1273–1333","1245–1270":"1245–1270","1242–1275":"1242–1275","Aft 1275":"pärast 1275","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1262":"1262","1272":"1272","28 April 1296":"28. aprill 1296","1270":"1270","3 September 1296":"3. september 1296","1245":"1245","1333":"1333","1289":"1289","1255":"1255","1254":"1254","Stitchill, Roxburghshire, Schotland":"Stitchill, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Huntly, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Huntly, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"f